      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    <p class="mb-6">The thing about their group was that it had never been chosen.<br>It had assembled itself the way most real things do — by accident, by proximity, by the specific chaos of a high school cafeteria on the first day of freshman year when assigned seating hadn't been assigned yet and five people had sat down at the same table without asking and then kept sitting there, every day, for three years, until the table became theirs by a kind of squatter's law nobody bothered to challenge.</p>
    <p class="mb-6">Marcus Chen sat down first, always, because Marcus was the kind of person who moved through the world at a slight forward lean — always slightly ahead of where he was, always arriving. He was built for confidence in a way that occasionally tipped into insufferable, and he knew it, and this self-awareness was the thing that kept him on the right side of tolerable. He read obsessively — not to be interesting, though it made him interesting, but because books were the only place where people talked at exactly the pace he wanted. He had strong opinions about everything. He apologized for approximately none of them.<br>Priya Nair sat across from him, which meant for three years they had been looking at each other over lunch, and for three years they had maintained a relationship best described as competitive mutual respect with occasional detours into something warmer that neither of them acknowledged. Priya was precise. Priya was the kind of precise that other people called intense until they needed something organized, at which point they called it invaluable. She kept color-coded notebooks. She tracked things — sleep, weather, the structural weaknesses in other people's arguments. She was almost always right and had learned, over years of social calibration, to deliver this fact with just enough softness that people thanked her instead of resenting her. Almost always. Not always.<br>Danny Walsh had sat down next to Marcus because there'd been an empty seat and Danny Walsh was constitutionally incapable of standing when sitting was available. Danny was large and loud and moved through the world with the energy of a golden retriever who had recently consumed something inadvisable. He played guitar — badly, enthusiastically, in a way that was somehow more charming than technical proficiency would have been. He laughed at everything, including things that weren't funny, but he laughed with such complete physical commitment — his whole body, his whole face, slightly delayed, like the joke had to travel a long distance to reach him — that you ended up laughing too, at him laughing, which he would have considered a success.<br>Simone Blake had sat down at the end of the table because the other tables had looked, to her eye, like bad cinematography. She saw everything in shots — framing, light, the way people positioned themselves relative to each other. She wanted to be a filmmaker and operated accordingly, narrating her own life in her head with a running internal voiceover that she would have died before admitting to. She was dry and occasionally cutting and the cuttingness was never quite mean enough to be unkind — it was more like precision. Like she'd seen the true shape of something and named it, and you couldn't be angry at the naming.<br>And Theo Park had sat down last, quietly, at the remaining seat, and had not said much for the first three weeks, and then had said exactly the right thing at exactly the right moment — something he'd been observing and waiting to say for three weeks, patient as architecture — and after that the group had understood that Theo was not quiet because he had nothing to offer. He was quiet because he was thinking, and what he produced when finished was worth the wait. He was the one who noticed things. He kept snacks in his backpack for other people's emergencies and never mentioned it. He was the kind of good that doesn't announce itself.<br>These five had been The Problem since freshman year — named so by a teacher who had said, exasperated, after their third combined detention, "You five are the problem," and they had adopted it immediately, with pride.</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <p class="mb-6">Junior year arrived the way junior years do — heavier than sophomore year, the future suddenly visible on the horizon in a way that was either exciting or nauseating depending on the hour.<br>And three weeks in, on a Wednesday in September, Jodelle Vasquez sat down.<br>She didn't ask. She appeared — that was the word Simone would use later, in her head, giving it cinematic weight. She appeared. Tray in hand, a single cup of black coffee that the cafeteria technically didn't serve to students but which Jodelle had apparently negotiated into existence through means unknown, and a bread roll she didn't eat. She placed the tray down at the one empty seat — the sixth chair that had existed at their table for three years as a kind of structural spare, the way houses have rooms nobody uses — and sat.<br>She was wearing all black. Not dramatically — not in the way that announced I am wearing all black, please observe. Just — black jeans, black shirt, a very old cardigan the color of charcoal that looked like it had been lived in for decades and possibly belonged to someone who no longer needed it. Her hair was dark and she wore it simply. She had rings on most of her fingers, all of them different, none of them matching. She looked like she had arrived from somewhere slightly to the left of wherever everyone else had come from.<br>She looked at the five of them, one by one, with a gaze that was unhurried and specific, as though she were reading a room she'd been briefed on.<br>"Hi," she said. "I'm Jodelle. I just moved here. Your table is the only one where people are actually talking to each other instead of at each other."<br>A short silence.<br>"That's a distinction most people don't make," Theo said.<br>"I know," she said, and picked up her coffee.<br>Marcus, who prided himself on clocking people quickly, found that he could not entirely clock her. She was — something. She held stillness in a way that felt active rather than passive, like she was choosing it. And she looked, while she held it, at a point just past whoever she was talking to, as though there were something in the background requiring periodic monitoring.<br>"New in town?" Priya said, in the tone of someone opening a diagnostic intake.<br>"New everywhere," Jodelle said. "My dad consults. We move." She said it without complaint, without the performance of suffering that most people applied to that statement. Just fact. We move. "Before this: Glasgow. Before that: Phoenix. Before that I was nine and don't have strong opinions."<br>"Glasgow," Danny said. "Like — Scotland Glasgow?"<br>"There is only one Glasgow," Jodelle said pleasantly.<br>"Do you have an accent?"<br>"I have many accents," she said. "They cancel each other out."<br>Danny considered this and then laughed — the big, full-body, slightly delayed laugh — and Jodelle watched it happen with the expression of someone observing a natural phenomenon they'd read about but not yet seen in person. Not unkind. Just — cataloguing.<br>"You can stay," Simone said, which was the same thing Theo would have said if Simone hadn't said it first.<br>Jodelle nodded once, as though this had been the expected outcome, and returned to her coffee.</p>
</div>`
