      text: `<div class="reading-font text-gray-300">
    <p class="mb-6">Camp Aldermoor was three hours north of Millhaven by road, and the road got progressively less interested in being a road as they went — four lanes to two lanes to a state route with grass growing in the median to a forestry road with a sign that said ALDERMOOR 4MI in reflective letters that caught the van headlights and threw them back.<br>They had rented a van. This had been Marcus's idea and Priya's execution — she had found the cheapest option within the required passenger capacity, calculated the gas cost split six ways, and distributed a packing list two weeks in advance that Danny had lost and Jodelle had never opened. Marcus drove because Marcus always drove, with the confidence of someone who had passed his test eighteen months ago and treated this as equivalent to decades of experience. Priya sat in the passenger seat with the printed confirmation and the camp's orientation document and occasionally said things like "the turn should be in about two miles" in the tone of someone who was not backseat driving because she was in the front seat.<br>Danny had the whole back row to himself and had fallen asleep before they'd left the city limits, which everyone agreed was impressive. Simone was filming — out the window, then the interior of the van, then Danny asleep with his mouth open, then the darkening trees as the road narrowed. Theo was reading. Jodelle was in the middle row, knees up, notebook open, drawing.<br>She had been drawing since they left. Theo, next to her, glanced over periodically. The drawing was the clearing — the same clearing, the foundation, the trees. More detailed now than any version he'd seen before. She'd added the lake in the background, visible between the trunks. She'd added light — the angle of it, late afternoon through heavy canopy. She'd added the figure at the northeast corner, clearer than usual. The jacket. The posture.<br>"You're drawing it again," he said, quietly, so the others wouldn't hear over the road noise and Danny's ambient snoring.<br>"More detail keeps coming," she said. "I want to get it down before it changes."<br>"Does it change?"<br>"Every time I see it, there's more. Like — " She paused. "Like when your eyes adjust in a dark room. Things that were shapeless become specific."<br>Theo looked at the drawing. At the man. At the northeast corner of the foundation, which she had crosshatched carefully, indicating something underneath the stone. Something below.<br>He looked out the window. Trees. Dark, dense, the headlights cutting a moving tunnel through them.<br>The sign said ALDERMOOR 1MI.<br>Jodelle closed the notebook and put it in her bag and looked out the window at the trees.<br>"We're close," she said. Not to anyone specifically. Just — noting it.</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <p class="mb-6">Camp Aldermoor revealed itself incrementally — first a gate, wooden, with the camp name in carved letters and a string of solar lights that had come on at dusk. Then a gravel road through the trees. Then, as the road curved, the horseshoe of cabins around the central lodge, the whole thing lit warmly against the dark of the forest, the lake visible beyond it, picking up the last of the evening sky.<br>Danny woke up as they came through the gate. He sat up, looked out the window, and said: "Oh. It's actually nice."<br>"You thought it wouldn't be?" Simone said.<br>"I thought it would be more — provisional," he said. "More tarp energy."<br>"It has cabins," Priya said. "I told you it had cabins."<br>"I know, but I didn't trust the brochure."<br>The brochure, Jodelle noted from the middle row, was accurate.<br>They parked in a gravel lot beside the lodge. Other cars and vans were already there — other campers arriving, other families doing the specific awkward choreography of drop-offs. The six of them climbed out into the warm evening and stood for a moment in the particular collective stillness of people arriving somewhere new, letting it land.<br>The air was different here. Cooler. Heavy with pine and water and the particular darkness of places where there are no streetlights. The lake caught the evening light in flat silver panels between the trees.<br>Danny breathed it in. "Okay," he said. "I'm glad we came."<br>"You've been here for thirty seconds," Marcus said.<br>"Thirty very good seconds," Danny said.<br>Jodelle was not looking at the lake or the lodge or the cabins. She was looking at the tree line to the west — a dark mass of old growth, denser than the managed forest around the camp, pressing up against the boundary where a low wooden fence ran between the manicured grass and whatever was beyond.<br>Theo followed her gaze. "Jo."<br>"The trees are older on that side," she said. "Pre-camp. That's old growth."<br>"How can you tell from here?"<br>"The canopy shape. The density. The managed trees all have the same approximate age — you can see it in the regularity of the height." She pointed. "Those don't. Those have been there a long time." She paused. "That's where it is."<br>"Where what is?"<br>She looked at him. "The clearing."<br>Before he could answer, a counselor appeared — young, twenty-something, with a clipboard and the expression of someone running on enthusiasm and insufficient sleep.<br>"Hey! Welcome to Aldermoor — I'm Reed, I'm the senior cohort lead. Can I get your names?"</p>
    <div class="text-center text-[#d4af37]/40 my-8 tracking-widest">✦ ✦ ✦</div>
    <p class="mb-6">Reed was twenty-four and had done this for four consecutive summers and retained, despite this, a quality of genuine enthusiasm that he deployed strategically and that the six of them found immediately readable.<br>"He likes the job but not the admin," Jodelle said, after Reed had ticked them off his list and directed them to Cabin Seven with detailed instructions that Marcus was already not following because Marcus preferred to orient himself. "He's been looking at his watch every ten minutes but not because he's bored — he's got a sequence he's running. He needs us all checked in by eight."<br>"You got all that from thirty seconds," Simone said.<br>"He's not complicated," Jodelle said, without unkindness. "He's a person who cares about things going well. Those are the easiest to read."<br>"And the hardest?" Marcus said, because Marcus couldn't help it.<br>Jodelle considered. "People who don't know what they want but think they do." A pause. "And people who know exactly what they want and have decided not to want it."<br>A small silence in which Priya and Marcus did not look at each other.<br>"Cabin Seven," Theo said.<br>They found Cabin Seven. It was wooden, warm-smelling, six bunks in two rows. Clean. Simple. The window on the west wall looked directly at the old-growth tree line, which Jodelle noted and said nothing about.<br>She took the bunk by the window.</p>
</div>`
